il's rural development and energy strategies yet in recent years sugar production has been widely criticized for its environmental and labor practices this study examines the relationship between rural development and sugarcane ethanol and cattle production in the state of sao paulo our results suggest that the value added components of sugarcane production which include sugar refining and ethanol production may have a strong positive affect on local human development in comparison to primary agricultural production activities and other land uses these results imply that sugar production when accompanied by a local processing industry can stimulate rural development however this paper also highlights the significant environmental and social harms generated by the sugar industry at large which may undermine its development benefits if not addressed download html+ go to site external http www sciencedirect com scienc parent research crop and livestock systems pressures projections and consequences globalization trade and the environment the case of brazil fsi stanford fse project topics biofuels biofuels land use and climate impacts energy sustainable development brazil search fse search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest the global costs of american ethanol rosamond l naylor walter p falcon the american interest vol 7 2 2011 html+ cover climbing the development ladder economic development and the evolution of occupations in rural china sandeep mohapatra scott rozelle jikun huang journal of development studies vol 42 6 2006 html+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4920 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
